exacting codes of rules, to the real-time control of officers via radio, and latterly the use of centralised computer systems to deliver key information. Police forces became pioneers in the adoption of many technologies – including telegraphs, telephones, office equipment, radio and computers – and this book explains why and how this happened, considering the role of national security in the adoption of many of these innovations. It will be of use to a range of disciplines, including history, criminology, and science and technology studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPolice administrationxHistoryxGreat Britain. 0aPolice administrationzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aPolicexHistoryxGreat Britain. 0aPolicexTechnological innovationsxGreat BritainxGreat Britain. 0aPolicexTechnological innovationszGreat Britain. 0aPolicezGreat BritainxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Law Enforcement.2bisacsh  aBureaucracy.  aCommunication.  aComputing.  aGreat Britain.  aHistory.  aPolice.  aTechnology.1 aWilliams, Chris A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packagez978311128357940uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610258440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526102584423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526102584/original  a978-3-11-128357-9  Manchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packageb2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles